SIMPLE: honky-tonk
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: honky-tonk
<hw>honky-tonk</hw> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>a cheap drinking and
dancing establishment; a cheap and tawdry nightclub.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> barrelhouse.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A district in which honky-tonks{1} are
found.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>honky-tonk</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: honky-tonk
<hw>honky-tonk</hw> <pos>a.</pos> <def>Pertaining to or resembling a
honky-tonk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Music)</fld> <def>Pertaining to a style of ragtime
piano music having a melody embellished with chords and syncopated
rhythms, accompanied by a bass in strict two-four or four-four time. It
is often played on an upright piano having its strings muffled to
produce a tinny sound; <as>as, a <ex>honky-tonk</ex> piano</as>.</def>
<au>RHUD</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Honor</ent>⟦br⟧
